# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] General elections were held in Italy on 27 January 1861, with a second round on 3 February.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] The newly elected Parliament first convened in Turin on 4 March 1861, where, thirteen days later, it declared the unification of the country as the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] The elections were carried out according to the 1848 electoral law of the Kingdom of Sardinia, in which only literate men over the age of 25 and paying a certain level of taxation were allowed to vote.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] Candidates were elected in single member constituencies, with a second round required in cases when no candidates received over 50% of the vote or the equivalent of one-third of the registered voters in the constituency.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] Pope Pius IX demanded that Catholics did not take part in the elections.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] The Historical Right was led by the former Prime Minister of the Kingdom of Sardinia, Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, a long-time statesman and a leading figure in the movement toward Italian unification.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] On the other hand, the bloc of the Historical Left was led by Urbano Rattazzi, a liberal politician who was among the founders of the Italian left-wing parliamentary group.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] In opposition to the two main blocs there were a third party known as The Extreme, a far-left coalition, under the leadership of Giuseppe Mazzini, an Italian revolutionary and a key figure of the Unification.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] Only 418,696 men of a total population of around 22 million were entitled to vote.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] Right-wing candidates emerged as the largest bloc in Parliament with around 43% of the 443 seats.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] They were largely aristocrats representing rentiers from the north of the country, and held moderate political views including loyalty to the crown and low government spending.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1861-italian-general-election] The right-wing leader Camillo Benso di Cavour was elected as the first Prime Minister in the history of Italy.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1865-italian-general-election] The Historical Right was led by the former Prime Minister of the Kingdom of Sardinia, Alfonso Ferrero La Marmora, a long-time general who fought during the Italian unification.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1865-italian-general-election] On the other hand, the bloc of the Historical Left was led by Urbano Rattazzi, a liberal politician who was between the founders of the Italian left-wing parliamentary group.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1865-italian-general-election] On 22 and 29 October only 504,263 men of a total population of around 23 million were entitled to vote.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1865-italian-general-election] Right-wing candidates emerged as the largest bloc in Parliament with around 41% of the 443 seats.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1865-italian-general-election] They were largely aristocrats representing rentiers from the north of the country, and held moderate political views including loyalty to the crown and low government spending; the general La Marmora was appointed prime minister by the king Victor Emmanuel II.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] Due to the restrictive Italian electoral laws of the time, only 504,265 Italian men, out of a total population of around 26 million, were entitled to vote.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] The voters were largely aristocrats, rentiers, and capitalists, who tended to hold moderate political views, including loyalty to the crown and low government spending.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] The opposition to Ricasoli was mainly organized by former prime minister Rattazzi, a moderate member of the Historical Left, who had entered into a coalition with the Historical Right in Piedmont fifteen years earlier.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] Even though Italian elections were officially non-partisan, the political conflict was so evident that the election became a match between these two political heavyweights.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] The 1867 election was a great defeat for Ricasoli, who thereafter retired to private life.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] However, while Ricasoli lost, Rattazzi did not receive a clear mandate, especially during the second part of the traditional two-round system.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] Many Independent candidates, who were ready to support any government that would support their local interests, were lukewarm supporters at best.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] Ultimately, Rattazzi was charged by the king to form a new government, but the fickle leftist faction abandoned him, forcing Rattazzi to form a new coalition.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] This was typical of Italian politics of the day, which were officially non-partisan with no structured parties.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] Voters instead were influenced more by localism and corruption, rather than loyalty to any leader or party.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] Rattazzi tried to form a centrist government consisting of his centre-left moderate faction, some Independents, and the Historical Right.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] These groups agreed to the coalition in order to later regain control.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] However, despite his efforts, Rattazzi's victory was ephemeral, similar to his first term as prime minister in 1862: barely six months later he was unable to stop an armed attack by a national hero, Giuseppe Garibaldi, upon the Papal State.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] The King, seeing that Rattazzi was ineffective, quickly forced his resignation.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1867-italian-general-election] Senator Luigi Federico Menabrea then took over as prime minister, with the Historical Right regaining full control of the government.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1870-italian-general-election] Only 530,018 men of a total population of around 26 million were entitled to vote.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1870-italian-general-election] The Historical Right was led by the Prime Minister of Italy, Giovanni Lanza, a conservative politician from Piedmont.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1870-italian-general-election] The bloc of the Historical Left was led by Urbano Rattazzi, a liberal politician and former Prime Minister, who led the left-wing for more than a decade.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1870-italian-general-election] The electoral result was controversial; in terms of percentages, Prime Minister Giovanni Lanza fully exploited the prestige of the Capture of Rome against his parliamentary opponents.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1870-italian-general-election] However, the turnout further declined after the Non expedit of Pope Pius IX, so that less than 1% of the total population of the country took part to this election.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1870-italian-general-election] The newly completed Italian State so revealed itself as a strict oligarchy with a deep fracture with its same population, creating a damage which was never really repaired.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1870-italian-general-election] After the election, Lanza was confirmed Prime Minister by the King.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1874-italian-general-election] Only 571,939 men of a total population of around 28 million were entitled to vote.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1874-italian-general-election] Right-wing candidates emerged as the largest bloc in Parliament with around 48% of the seats in Parliament.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1874-italian-general-election] This was the last election in which the Historical Right faction emerged as the largest.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1874-italian-general-election] However, in the Italian non-partisan political system, hugely affected by localism and corruption, their bet was equivalent to an all-in that afterwards they lost.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1874-italian-general-election] The election did not give to Minghetti the advantage he was hoping, especially for the high support to the opposition in Southern Italy.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1874-italian-general-election] His government survived, but the bipolarisation of the Parliament he had imposed, strengthened the Historical Left so that it could take the leadership of the country.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1874-italian-general-election] Two years later, MPs from Tuscany became dissatisfied with the government after it refused to intervene in the financial problems of Florence.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1874-italian-general-election] The government was defeated on a vote on nationalising railways on 18 March 1876 and was forced to resign.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1874-italian-general-election] As a result, Agostino Depretis, leader of the left-wing bloc, became Prime Minister, with 414 of the 508 MPs supporting the government.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1876-italian-general-election] The Historical Left was led by the current Prime Minister of Italy, Agostino Depretis, who became head of the government and early elections were called.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1876-italian-general-election] On the other hand, the bloc of the Historical Right was led by Marco Minghetti, former prime minister from Bologna.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1876-italian-general-election] The election on 5 and 12 November was a snap one, and it came after MPs from Tuscany became dissatisfied with the government of Minghetti following its refusal to intervene in the financial problems of Florence.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1876-italian-general-election] The government was defeated on a vote on nationalising railways on 18 March 1876 and was forced to resign and Depretis was appointed prime minister.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1876-italian-general-election] For the first time, the left-wing won an election, taking 414 of the 508 seats, of which 12 were extreme left-wingers.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1876-italian-general-election] Only 605,007 men of a total population of around 28 million were entitled to vote.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1880-italian-general-election] The Historical Left was led by the Prime Minister of Italy, Agostino Depretis, longtime Prime Minister of Italy.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1880-italian-general-election] The bloc of the Historical Right was led by Marco Minghetti, a conservative politician and former Prime Minister, from Bologna.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1880-italian-general-election] A third large parliamentary group was the Dissident Left, composed by former members of the Left, which were against the alliance with the Right.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1880-italian-general-election] Also known as *La Pentarchia* (The Pentarchy), its main leader was Giuseppe Zanardelli, a jurisconsult from Brescia.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1880-italian-general-election] The Historical Left group emerged as the largest in Parliament, although left-wing dissidents won 119 of the 508 seats, becoming the third parliamentary group.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1880-italian-general-election] Only 621,896 men of a total population of around 29 million were entitled to vote.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1880-italian-general-election] Benedetto Cairoli was confirmed Prime Minister by the king Umberto I.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The **1979 European Parliament election in Italy** was held on 10 June 1979.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] As the 1979 Italian general election was held on 3 June, just a week before, the lack of matching between the two elections caused much controversy for wasting public money.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The pure party-list proportional representation was the traditional electoral system of the Italian Republic since its foundation in 1946, so it was naturally adopted to elect the Italian representatives to the European Parliament.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Two levels were used: a national level to divide seats between parties, and a constituency level to distribute them between candidates.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Italian regions were united in 5 constituencies, each electing a group of deputies.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] At national level, seats were divided between party lists using the largest remainder method with Hare quota.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] All seats gained by each party were automatically distributed to their local open lists and their most voted candidates.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Seats are allocated to party lists on a national basis using an electoral quota, with the residue given to the lists with the largest excess over whole quotas.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] An electoral quota is then calculated for each list and used to allocate seats to each list in each of the five electoral regions.
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] As the election took place just a week after the general election, it gave a similar result; however, the minor importance of the European ballot caused a lower turnout, which particularly punished the two major parties, Christian Democracy (DC) and the Italian Communist Party (PCI).
[src:1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The small Italian Liberal Party (PLI) had a breath of fresh air from this vote, doubling its percentage compared to seven days before.
